  "## How the operators avoided detection",
  "",
  "Reading the data, the operators were measurably sophisticated about hiding their footprints. We list the anti-detection patterns because they distinguish this from amateur hackathon farming and matter for anyone running a similar investigation on a future contest:",
  "",
  "- **No same-block voter clustering.** Casper mainnet produces roughly one block every 32 seconds. Across the 10-day voting window, 1,825 distinct blocks contained at least one FANR2 vote-deploy. Of those, only 29 blocks (1.6%) contained ≥2 distinct voters; **zero blocks contained 3+ distinct voters**. The largest single-block voter cluster was 2. A naive bot operator firing votes from a single machine would cluster many in the same block (mempool batching is the cheap default). The operators here paced their submissions to scatter across blocks — a deliberate anti-detection measure that costs operator time but makes mempool-level clustering analysis return nothing.",
  "",
  "- **No same-second batch voter funding.** For each of the 749 traced voters, we have the timestamp of their first incoming CSPR transfer. We bucketed by (funder, timestamp-to-the-second). **Zero buckets contained 2+ voters funded in the same second by the same sender.** The most obvious bot-spawn signature (one transaction funding many wallets) is absent — the operators funded each wallet via a separate transaction, paying the per-tx gas overhead in exchange for an audit that doesn't return a smoking gun on first-pass batch-funding analysis.",
  "",
  "- **Cascading peer-to-peer funding.** 481 of 749 voters (64.2%) were funded by a wallet that is itself a voter. Apex funder `74ab92ce…` voted, then funded 106 other voters. Apex funder `41e4339e…` voted, then funded 88 others. The operators built a multi-generation cascade — top wallet → mid-tier wallets → leaf voter wallets — so that no single \"bank\" wallet has the obvious shape of funding hundreds of voters. The on-chain pyramid we identified only resolves when you trace each voter four or five hops upstream.",
  "",
  "- **Realistic time-of-day distribution.** Hour-of-day UTC voting counts peak between 12:00–13:00 and 18:00–21:00 UTC, with the lowest activity at 02:00–04:00 UTC — consistent with the global daytime distribution of real human users. A naive bot would fire votes around the clock at off-peak hours; the operators here calibrated to match human activity patterns. The realistic timing distribution makes raw \"votes per hour\" histograms reveal nothing.",
